    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey im studying for my ml midterm and im kinda stuck on regularization. can u explain the main difference between L1 and L2 regularization and how they actually affect the model coefficients differently?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Sure, I can help with that! L1 regularization, also known as Lasso, adds a penalty equal to the absolute value of the magnitude of coefficients. This can lead to some coefficients being shrunk to zero, effectively performing feature selection. On the other hand, L2 regularization, also known as Ridge, adds a penalty equal to the square of the magnitude of coefficients, which tends to shrink coefficients but rarely makes them zero. This can help to reduce overfitting by distributing the error among all the terms. So, in a nutshell, L1 can lead to sparse solutions, while L2 leads to more compact ones.",
      "source": "target",
