      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense but i dont really get the \"why\" behind it. like why does l1 actually force them to zero while l2 just makes them small? is there a way to visualize that or an intuition for why the math works out that way?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Absolutely, let's dive into the \"why\" behind it. L1 regularization works by adding a term to the loss function that is the sum of the absolute values of the coefficients. This creates a piecewise linear function with koses (sharp corners) at the origin. When you minimize this function, the solution often ends up at one of these corners, which corresponds to having a coefficient of zero. It's like a game where you try to minimize the sum of the absolute values of the weights, and the best strategy is to have some weights be zero.\n\nOn the other hand, L2 regularization adds a term that is the sum of the squares of the coefficients. This creates a smooth, convex function with no sharp corners. When you minimize this function, the solution often ends up at a point where all the weights are small but not necessarily zero. It's like a game where you try to minimize the sum of the squares of the weights, and the best strategy is to have all weights be small.\n\nSo, the math behind it is that L1 regularization creates a function with sharp corners at the origin, which leads to some weights being zero, while L2 regularization creates a smooth, convex function, which leads to small weights.",
