      "role": "user",
      "content": "ok i think i get the geometry of the corners vs the smooth circle thing now. but i'm still struggling with how to actually decide which one to use in a real project. like if i have a dataset with 1000 features but i suspect only a few are actually important, which one is better and how do i know for sure?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Great question! If you suspect that only a few features are actually important, L1 regularization (Lasso) might be a better choice. Lasso can help you identify the most important features by shrinking some coefficients to zero, effectively performing feature selection. This can be particularly useful when you have a large number of features and you want to reduce the complexity of your model.\n\nTo decide which one to use, you can try both L1 and L2 regularization on your dataset and compare the results. You can use cross-validation to evaluate the performance of the models with different regularization strengths. If Lasso performs better and you see that some coefficients are shrunk to zero, it indicates that those features are not important. On the other hand, if L2 regularization performs better, it means that all the features are important and you should use L2 regularization.\n\nAnother way to decide is to use domain knowledge. If you have a good understanding of the problem and the features, you can use that knowledge to guide your choice. For example, if you know that some features are likely to be more important than others, you can use Lasso to select the most important ones.\n\nIn summary, Lasso is generally better when you suspect that",
